1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:08,040
You're listening to: Building Backends for AI Agents: Idempotency, Retries & State (2026).

2
00:00:08,040 --> 00:00:14,338
AI agents retry, run for minutes, and call your APIs in unpredictable loops.

3
00:00:14,338 --> 00:00:17,632
The backend is where agent reliability lives.

4
00:00:17,632 --> 00:00:27,031
A practical guide to idempotency, safe retries, durable state, and observability for agent-facing systems in 2026.

5
00:00:27,031 --> 00:00:28,112
Let's get started.

6
00:00:28,112 --> 00:00:35,564
There's a line going around in 2026 that I think is exactly right: the backend is where agent reliability lives.

7
00:00:35,564 --> 00:00:48,293
All the attention goes to the model and the prompts, but when an AI agent does something wrong — charges twice, corrupts state, loops forever — the failure is almost always in the backend it was calling, not the model.

8
00:00:48,293 --> 00:01:00,396
Agents are just a new, unusually chaotic kind of API client, and most backends were not built for a client that retries aggressively, runs for minutes, and calls your endpoints in loops it decides at runtime.

9
00:01:00,396 --> 00:01:05,528
This is a practical guide to building backends that stay correct when an agent is driving.

10
00:01:05,528 --> 00:01:15,961
It pulls together patterns I've written about individually — idempotency keys, event-driven design, rate limiting — into one mental model for agent-facing systems.

11
00:01:15,961 --> 00:01:19,411
Now, let's talk about Why agents break backends that humans don't.

12
00:01:19,411 --> 00:01:27,776
A human client is predictable: one click, one request, a sensible pause, a retry only when they're frustrated.

13
00:01:27,776 --> 00:01:29,663
An agent is the opposite:

14
00:01:29,663 --> 00:01:31,983
It retries reflexively.

15
00:01:31,983 --> 00:01:39,519
When a tool call times out or returns an error, the agent's loop often just calls it again — sometimes many times, fast..

16
00:01:39,519 --> 00:01:40,697
It runs long.

17
00:01:40,697 --> 00:01:46,947
A single agent task can span minutes of tool calls, far past a normal HTTP timeout..

18
00:01:46,947 --> 00:01:49,639
It calls tools in runtime-decided loops.

19
00:01:49,639 --> 00:01:54,627
You can't predict the sequence or the volume; the agent composes it on the fly..

20
00:01:54,627 --> 00:01:56,382
It acts on stale beliefs.

21
00:01:56,382 --> 00:02:01,081
An agent may decide to "create the order" based on context that's already changed..

22
00:02:01,081 --> 00:02:12,343
Each of these maps to a backend property you must now guarantee: idempotency, durable long-running execution, rate limiting and loop-breaking, and consistent state.

23
00:02:12,343 --> 00:02:16,562
Get those four right and agents become a manageable client.

24
00:02:16,562 --> 00:02:23,966
Skip them and you get the 2026 version of the double-charge bug — except the agent does it ten times in four seconds.

25
00:02:23,966 --> 00:02:25,084
Moving on to 1.

26
00:02:25,084 --> 00:02:28,257
Idempotency is non-negotiable now.

27
00:02:28,257 --> 00:02:33,004
For human-facing APIs, idempotency is good hygiene.

28
00:02:33,004 --> 00:02:40,324
For agent-facing APIs, it is mandatory, because the agent will retry, and you have no control over when.

29
00:02:40,324 --> 00:02:45,600
Every state-changing tool an agent can call must be safe to call repeatedly.

30
00:02:45,600 --> 00:02:54,963
The pattern is the same one I detailed in idempotency keys: the caller supplies a key, you claim it atomically, and you replay the stored result on duplicates.

31
00:02:54,963 --> 00:02:59,519
The practical twist for agents: you often have to generate the key for them.

32
00:02:59,519 --> 00:03:02,115
Many agent frameworks don't supply one.

33
00:03:02,115 --> 00:03:15,949
A robust approach is to derive a deterministic key from (agent_run_id, tool_name, canonical_args_hash) — so the same logical action within a run collapses to one key even if the agent doesn't think to send one.

34
00:03:15,949 --> 00:03:20,312
Next up: 2. Make destructive tools hard to fire by accident.

35
00:03:20,312 --> 00:03:23,605
Idempotency stops duplicate harm.

36
00:03:23,605 --> 00:03:28,377
You also want to limit first-time harm from an agent that misunderstands its task.

37
00:03:28,377 --> 00:03:29,675
Two cheap guards:

38
00:03:29,675 --> 00:03:32,824
Confirmation tokens for irreversible actions.

39
00:03:32,824 --> 00:03:40,072
A "delete customer" tool returns a preview + a token; the action only executes when called again with that token.

40
00:03:40,072 --> 00:03:44,026
This forces a two-step the agent must consciously complete..

41
00:03:44,026 --> 00:03:47,247
Dry-run by default for high-blast-radius tools.

42
00:03:47,247 --> 00:03:50,997
Return what would happen; require an explicit commit: true.

43
00:03:50,997 --> 00:03:55,072
Agents tend to do the safe thing when the safe thing is the default..

44
00:03:55,072 --> 00:04:06,983
These aren't agent-specific inventions — they're the same defensive instincts behind good REST API design — but agents raise the stakes enough that they're worth making mandatory for anything destructive.

45
00:04:06,983 --> 00:04:08,413
Let's explore 3.

46
00:04:08,413 --> 00:04:11,718
Rate limit per agent run, and break loops.

47
00:04:11,718 --> 00:04:14,963
A buggy agent can hammer a tool in a tight loop.

48
00:04:14,963 --> 00:04:20,576
Standard per-user rate limiting helps, but the more useful unit for agents is the agent run.

49
00:04:20,576 --> 00:04:23,617
Track calls per agent_run_id and:

50
00:04:23,642 --> 00:04:25,863
Cap total tool calls per run.

51
00:04:25,863 --> 00:04:33,604
A hard ceiling ("this run may call tools 200 times") turns an infinite loop into a bounded, debuggable failure..

52
00:04:33,604 --> 00:04:34,950
Detect repetition.

53
00:04:34,950 --> 00:04:45,611
If the same (tool, args_hash) is called N times in a run with no state change, that's a loop — return an error that tells the agent to stop, not the same result that keeps it spinning..

54
00:04:45,611 --> 00:04:54,601
The token-bucket and gateway patterns in rate limiting & API gateway patterns apply directly; you're just keying them on the run instead of the user.

55
00:04:54,601 --> 00:04:55,815
Now let's look at 4.

56
00:04:55,815 --> 00:05:00,611
State: agents need durable, inspectable execution.

57
00:05:00,611 --> 00:05:09,902
Because agent tasks are long and multi-step, you cannot hold their progress in a request handler's memory — a deploy, crash, or timeout would lose it.

58
00:05:09,902 --> 00:05:18,652
Agent backends need durable state: the run, its steps, and its tool results persisted so the work can resume and so you can inspect what happened.

59
00:05:18,652 --> 00:05:21,536
This is where event-driven thinking pays off.

60
00:05:21,536 --> 00:05:33,243
Model an agent run as an append-only event log — run_started, tool_called, tool_result, step_completed — exactly the event-driven architecture pattern.

61
00:05:33,243 --> 00:05:34,253
Benefits:

62
00:05:34,253 --> 00:05:35,527
Recoverability.

63
00:05:35,527 --> 00:05:39,457
Rebuild run state by replaying its events after a crash..

64
00:05:39,457 --> 00:05:40,575
Auditability.

65
00:05:40,575 --> 00:05:45,382
When an agent does something surprising, the event log is the trace of why..

66
00:05:45,382 --> 00:05:47,065
Idempotent resume.

67
00:05:47,065 --> 00:05:52,474
Combined with the action keys above, you can re-drive a run without repeating completed side effects..

68
00:05:52,474 --> 00:06:02,618
For long-running execution specifically, don't block the HTTP request for minutes — kick the work to a durable queue and let the agent poll or subscribe.

69
00:06:02,618 --> 00:06:08,808
I cover that pattern in depth in designing async, long-running APIs for AI agents.

70
00:06:08,808 --> 00:06:10,262
Now, let's talk about 5.

71
00:06:10,262 --> 00:06:13,784
Observability: you cannot debug what you cannot see.

72
00:06:13,784 --> 00:06:16,644
Agent failures are weird and intermittent.

73
00:06:16,644 --> 00:06:22,029
Without tracing, "the agent did something bad yesterday" is unfixable.

74
00:06:22,029 --> 00:06:35,154
Instrument every tool call with the agent_run_id as a trace/correlation ID, and emit the same percentile metrics you'd use anywhere — the Prometheus/Grafana/Jaeger stack works unchanged.

75
00:06:35,154 --> 00:06:45,863
The one addition for agents: log the arguments and decision, not just latency, because the interesting failure is usually "why did it call this tool with these args," not "how slow was it."

76
00:06:45,863 --> 00:06:49,168
Moving on to The checklist for an agent-ready backend.

77
00:06:49,168 --> 00:06:56,632
Every state-changing tool is idempotent — caller key or server-derived (run, tool, args) key..

78
00:06:56,632 --> 00:07:01,717
Destructive tools are two-step — confirmation tokens or dry-run-by-default..

79
00:07:01,717 --> 00:07:06,873
Rate limits and loop detection are keyed on the agent run, with a hard call ceiling..

80
00:07:06,873 --> 00:07:13,051
Runs are durable, append-only event logs — recoverable, auditable, resumable..

81
00:07:13,051 --> 00:07:17,906
Long work is async, off the request path (details here)..

82
00:07:17,906 --> 00:07:21,885
Every tool call is traced by run ID, with arguments captured..

83
00:07:21,885 --> 00:07:23,760
Next up: The takeaway.

84
00:07:23,760 --> 00:07:35,214
The agent era doesn't require exotic new backend theory — it requires you to actually apply the reliability patterns we already knew, because the new client punishes every shortcut.

85
00:07:35,214 --> 00:07:41,789
Idempotency, durable state, run-scoped rate limits, and tracing were "nice to have" for human traffic.

86
00:07:41,789 --> 00:07:48,207
For agents they're the difference between a tool an agent can safely use and a footgun it fires on your behalf.

87
00:07:48,207 --> 00:07:56,452
Build the backend as if a fast, slightly confused client is in control of it — because in 2026, one is.

88
